In C++, you can start a new process and connect one file descriptor to its input and output using the `fork()` and `exec()` family of functions, along with file descriptor redirection. Here's a basic example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int pipefd[2];
    pid_t pid;

    // Create a pipe
    if (pipe(pipefd) == -1) {
        perror("pipe");
        return 1;
    }

    // Fork a child process
    pid = fork();
    if (pid < 0) {  // Error
        perror("fork");
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) {  // Child process
        // Close the write end of the pipe
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Redirection: file descriptor 0 (stdin) to the read end of the pipe
        dup2(pipefd[0], STDIN_FILENO);

        // Close the pipe read end
        close(pipefd[0]);

        // Execute the command
        execlp("command", "command", (char*)0);
        perror("execlp");
        _exit(1);  // Exit, in case execlp() fails
    } else {  // Parent process
        // Close the read end of the pipe
        close(pipefd[0]);

        // Do something with the write end of the pipe (e.g., write to it)
        write(pipefd[1], "Hello, child process!", 21);

        // Close the write end of the pipe
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Wait for the child process to finish
        wait(NULL);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the child process is redirected to use the read end of the pipe for its standard input and standard output. The parent process writes to the write end of the pipe to communicate with the child process. Adjust the command and the write message as needed for your specific use case.
